# Dark Mode

## Overview

Light/dark mode theming is powered by `next-themes` in both `apps/web` and `apps/admin`. The theme is applied via the `.dark` CSS class on `<html>`, toggled by a `ThemeProvider` wrapping the app and a `ThemeToggle` button in the top-right corner.

## Architecture

- **`next-themes`** manages theme state (system / light / dark), persists to `localStorage`, and applies the `.dark` class
- **`theme.css`** (generated by `pnpm sync-config`) defines both `:root` (light) and `.dark` CSS custom properties using OKLCH colors
- **`ThemeProvider`** wraps the app in `layout.tsx` as the outermost client boundary
- **`ThemeToggle`** is a client component that reads and toggles the current theme

## Key Files

### Web (`apps/web`)

- `src/components/theme-provider.tsx` — `ThemeProvider` wrapper around `next-themes`
- `src/components/theme-toggle.tsx` — Sun/Moon icon button, uses `useTranslation()` for aria-labels
- `src/app/layout.tsx` — `ThemeProvider` wraps all other providers

### Admin (`apps/admin`)

- `src/components/theme-provider.tsx` — same `ThemeProvider` pattern
- `src/components/theme-toggle.tsx` — same toggle pattern (no i18n since admin has no i18n setup)
- `src/app/layout.tsx` — `ThemeProvider` wraps `{children}`

### React Native (`apps/react-native`)

React Native uses `useColorScheme()` from `react-native` (follows OS theme automatically). There is no `next-themes` dependency.

## ThemeProvider Configuration

```typescript
<NextThemesProvider
  attribute="class"
  defaultTheme="system"
  enableSystem
  disableTransitionOnChange
>
```

- `attribute="class"` — toggles `.dark` class on `<html>` (matches `theme.css` selectors)
- `defaultTheme="system"` — respects OS preference on first visit
- `enableSystem` — reacts to OS-level theme changes
- `disableTransitionOnChange` — prevents flash of incorrect theme on toggle

## Tailwind CSS v4 Class-Based Dark Mode

Tailwind CSS v4 defaults to `@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)` for `dark:` variants. Since `next-themes` uses the `.dark` class, every Next.js app's `globals.css` must include:

```css
@custom-variant dark (&:where(.dark, .dark *));
```

Without this, `dark:` utility classes follow the OS preference instead of the `next-themes` toggle, causing light mode to show dark styles when the OS is in dark mode.

## Dark Mode in CSS

Use Tailwind's `dark:` variant for component-level overrides:

```tsx
<div className="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
<p className="text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">
```

For most cases, prefer semantic color tokens (`bg-background`, `text-foreground`, `bg-card`, etc.) which automatically switch between light and dark via the CSS custom properties in `theme.css`. Only use `dark:` overrides when a component needs colors outside the token system.

## Hydration Safety

`ThemeToggle` renders a disabled placeholder until mounted (avoids SSR/client mismatch). The `<html>` tag includes `suppressHydrationWarning` in all Next.js layouts.

```typescript
const [mounted, setMounted] = useState(false);
useEffect(() => { setMounted(true); }, []);
if (!mounted) return <Button disabled>...</Button>;
```

## New Page / Feature Checklist

Every new page, feature component, or screen **must** support both light and dark mode. Treat this as a requirement equal to i18n or mobile responsiveness.

1. **Use semantic tokens first** — `bg-background`, `text-foreground`, `bg-card`, `text-muted-foreground`, `border-border`, etc. These auto-switch via `theme.css` and require zero extra work.
2. **Audit every hardcoded color** — any raw Tailwind color (`bg-white`, `text-gray-500`, `from-blue-300`, `border-gray-200`, etc.) needs a `dark:` counterpart or must be replaced with a semantic token.
3. **Check gradients** — gradient stops (`from-*`, `via-*`, `to-*`) don't use semantic tokens, so always pair them with `dark:from-*`, `dark:via-*`, `dark:to-*`.
4. **Check SVGs and inline styles** — hardcoded `fill`, `stroke`, and `style={{ color }}` values don't respond to Tailwind's `dark:` variant. Use `currentColor`, CSS variables, or conditional classes.
5. **Check shadows and overlays** — `shadow-*` and `bg-black/50` overlays may need `dark:shadow-*` or adjusted opacity for dark backgrounds.
6. **Check images and icons** — ensure sufficient contrast on both backgrounds. Use `dark:invert` or provide alternate assets (`logo-light.svg` / `logo-dark.svg`) where needed.
7. **Test both modes** — toggle the theme and visually verify the page in both light and dark before considering the feature complete.

### Quick reference — common pairings

| Light | Dark |
|---|---|
| `bg-white` | `dark:bg-gray-950` |
| `bg-gray-50` | `dark:bg-gray-900` |
| `text-gray-500` | `dark:text-gray-400` |
| `text-gray-900` | `dark:text-gray-100` |
| `border-gray-200` | `dark:border-gray-800` |
| `from-blue-300` | `dark:from-blue-950` |
| `shadow-lg` | `dark:shadow-gray-900/30` |

## Rules

- **DO** support both light and dark mode in every new page, feature, and component — no exceptions
- **DO** wrap the app with `ThemeProvider` as the outermost provider in `layout.tsx`
- **DO** add `suppressHydrationWarning` to `<html>` in every Next.js layout that uses `ThemeProvider`
- **DO** prefer semantic Tailwind tokens (`bg-background`, `text-foreground`, `border-border`) over raw colors — they auto-switch with theme
- **DO** use `dark:` variant for overrides that fall outside the token system
- **DO** audit every hardcoded color in new components and add a `dark:` counterpart
- **DO** guard `ThemeToggle` rendering with a `mounted` state to prevent hydration mismatches
- **DO** include `@custom-variant dark (&:where(.dark, .dark *));` in `globals.css` for every Next.js app — required for `next-themes` class-based toggling in Tailwind CSS v4
- **DO** test new features in both light and dark mode before marking them complete
- **DO NOT** ship a page or component that only looks correct in one theme
- **DO NOT** manually edit `theme.css` — it is generated by `pnpm sync-config`
- **DO NOT** remove the `@custom-variant dark` directive — without it, `dark:` utilities follow OS preference instead of the theme toggle
- **DO NOT** use `next-themes` in React Native — use `useColorScheme()` from `react-native` instead
- **DO NOT** use `forcedTheme` unless a specific page must be single-theme (e.g., marketing pages)
- **DO NOT** conditionally render entirely different component trees based on theme — use CSS classes
- **DO NOT** use hardcoded colors in SVG `fill`/`stroke` without also handling dark mode (use `currentColor` or CSS variables)
